WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:12.500
In January of 2021, Alaska was on the cusp of the most highly anticipated vaccine launch

00:00:12.500 --> 00:00:15.240
in 50 years, the COVID vaccine.

00:00:15.240 --> 00:00:20.959
So as the state began to roll out shots to senior citizens aged 65 and above, the hottest

00:00:20.959 --> 00:00:24.760
ticket in town was a COVID-19 vaccine appointment.

00:00:24.760 --> 00:00:28.500
So when a batch of appointments would come online, those would be snatched up within

00:00:28.500 --> 00:00:30.900
hours or sometimes even minutes.

00:00:30.900 --> 00:00:33.419
And back in those days, everybody needed an online appointment.

00:00:33.419 --> 00:00:36.380
You couldn't just walk in and get your COVID-19 vaccine.

00:00:36.380 --> 00:00:39.860
So it's a really exciting time, but we found out pretty quickly that the website the state

00:00:39.860 --> 00:00:44.380
was using to get people signed up was not working well for senior citizens.

00:00:44.380 --> 00:00:47.340
It was hiding the appointments in several pages of results.

00:00:47.340 --> 00:00:51.220
It was made for healthcare professionals working on desktop computers, but it wasn't working

00:00:51.220 --> 00:00:52.220
for people on the phones.

00:00:52.220 --> 00:00:53.220
The maps were distorted.

00:00:53.220 --> 00:00:57.619
It's showing the Sacramento County Jail instead of the Anchorage Health Department here.

00:00:57.740 --> 00:01:00.180
And so we started to hear from senior citizens that they were struggling, that they were

00:01:00.180 --> 00:01:03.619
not making it through the appointment registration process.

00:01:03.619 --> 00:01:08.660
And so at this really critical juncture, the senior citizens are starting to contact us

00:01:08.660 --> 00:01:12.080
and saying that some are at the cusp of actually giving up.

00:01:12.080 --> 00:01:16.540
And at this really important moment of the pandemic, senior citizens are frustrated,

00:01:16.540 --> 00:01:20.879
the state is frustrated, and I'm frustrated, especially when I learned that there's no

00:01:20.879 --> 00:01:24.760
changes and no improvements that could come to the website anytime soon.

00:01:24.760 --> 00:01:28.879
But I knew that there must be a way to improve this website experience, and I knew I had

00:01:28.879 --> 00:01:30.639
to at least try.

00:01:30.639 --> 00:01:32.000
So my name is Ben Matheson.

00:01:32.000 --> 00:01:35.120
I work for the Anchorage Innovation Team in Anchorage, Alaska.

00:01:35.120 --> 00:01:39.720
We're a small team inside city government that uses data, human-centered design, and

00:01:39.720 --> 00:01:41.440
technology to solve problems.

00:01:41.440 --> 00:01:45.599
So we try to improve the lives of residents, solve problems with city departments, and

00:01:45.599 --> 00:01:47.400
save money.

00:01:47.400 --> 00:01:51.080
So today I'm going to tell you about how we built a vaccine finder for the state of Alaska

00:01:51.080 --> 00:01:56.360
in one week using R. And I hope to show you how R is a great tool for rapid prototyping

00:01:56.360 --> 00:01:58.040
and rapid building of products.

00:01:58.040 --> 00:02:01.959
And after this, I hope that you can better appreciate how you have the tools and abilities

00:02:01.959 --> 00:02:06.080
to really make some cool custom rapid products.

00:02:06.080 --> 00:02:10.080
And so before we started building anything, we wanted to validate if there was a problem

00:02:10.080 --> 00:02:12.660
and find out exactly what this problem was.

00:02:12.660 --> 00:02:17.240
So we got on the phone with senior citizens as they were trying to sign up for their vaccines,

00:02:17.240 --> 00:02:19.080
and we found out a few things.

00:02:19.080 --> 00:02:23.160
One is that they are struggling through a complex website.

00:02:23.160 --> 00:02:26.580
We learned that they're struggling with some pretty complicated health questions that show

00:02:26.580 --> 00:02:32.460
up in these vaccine registration systems, and also learning that the adult children

00:02:32.460 --> 00:02:37.600
sometimes of seniors are the ones who are actually signing up for appointments.

00:02:37.600 --> 00:02:41.119
And so we tried to narrow the problem a little bit to, you know, how can we help Anchorage

00:02:41.119 --> 00:02:45.000
senior citizens who want their vaccine really quickly find that appointment so that they

00:02:45.000 --> 00:02:47.119
can get their vaccine?

00:02:47.119 --> 00:02:50.880
And so before we started building anything big, we wanted to do a no-budget build, an

00:02:50.880 --> 00:02:53.440
MVP, a minimum viable product.

00:02:53.440 --> 00:02:58.080
So in this case, what is the smallest, fastest, quickest thing that we can make that proves

00:02:58.080 --> 00:03:01.399
that there is value, get it into the hands of people, and see whether we're helping the

00:03:01.399 --> 00:03:04.460
problem or if we need to go in a totally different direction?

00:03:04.460 --> 00:03:07.199
And so this was a literally Friday night project.

00:03:07.199 --> 00:03:10.880
It's Friday night in early January, and I picked up the tools that I use when I want

00:03:10.880 --> 00:03:15.320
to make something fast and easy and maybe not easy, but I picked up dplyr.

00:03:15.320 --> 00:03:20.279
I use Stringer and Lubridate, and we're trying to capture vaccine appointments as they come

00:03:20.279 --> 00:03:25.039
online and as they disappear, and we learned pretty quickly that there's no API coming.

00:03:25.039 --> 00:03:28.839
There's no programmatic access to vaccine appointments in Anchorage.

00:03:28.839 --> 00:03:30.199
So it's time to scrape.

00:03:30.199 --> 00:03:35.559
So we used Rvest to scrape the vaccine web pages.

00:03:35.559 --> 00:03:39.160
And anybody who's ever used a web scraper knows that it's like trying to create order

00:03:39.160 --> 00:03:40.240
from chaos.

00:03:40.240 --> 00:03:44.039
You know, you find a div that appears to have the information that you're looking for.

00:03:44.039 --> 00:03:47.399
You know, it's border gray 200 is the div that we want here.

00:03:47.399 --> 00:03:53.279
We go grab that div and extract the text from it, and from that text, we try to turn that

00:03:53.279 --> 00:03:57.119
into structured data that serves our needs.

00:03:57.119 --> 00:04:02.479
So rip it apart, mutate, modify, put it back together, and make structured data out of

00:04:02.479 --> 00:04:04.000
this text.

00:04:04.000 --> 00:04:05.000
So we're scraping.

00:04:05.000 --> 00:04:08.639
We're able to capture that data, but then it's time for a really quick front end of

00:04:08.639 --> 00:04:11.360
how do you discover vaccine appointments?

00:04:11.360 --> 00:04:15.320
And because this website was a reaction to an overly complicated website, we wanted to

00:04:15.320 --> 00:04:18.640
go with something super simple, super fast, super lightweight.

00:04:18.640 --> 00:04:21.239
And so I went with an HTML table.

00:04:21.239 --> 00:04:26.040
So on the left is the prototype that came together after a few hours on a Friday night.

00:04:26.040 --> 00:04:31.720
It's a web scraping service that scrapes every 60 seconds to try to find those appointments

00:04:31.720 --> 00:04:36.040
as they come up, as they disappear, and we show those in a really simple format.

00:04:36.040 --> 00:04:39.679
No filtering, no menus, no maps, no anything.

00:04:40.079 --> 00:04:44.079
It's how do you really quickly find those actual vaccine appointments?

00:04:44.079 --> 00:04:45.200
And then it's time to test.

00:04:45.200 --> 00:04:49.839
So we've got this very prototype website, and we send it to people who are working on

00:04:49.839 --> 00:04:51.239
the Vaccine Call Center.

00:04:51.239 --> 00:04:56.239
It's a team of about 40 people who spend all day on the phone with senior citizens trying

00:04:56.239 --> 00:04:58.040
to help them sign up for appointments.

00:04:58.040 --> 00:05:00.399
And they're able to give us some really good feedback.

00:05:00.399 --> 00:05:03.799
They're able to see if it's helping.

00:05:03.799 --> 00:05:04.799
And it did help.

00:05:04.799 --> 00:05:07.019
They're able to kind of use it as a power tool.

00:05:07.019 --> 00:05:11.299
This was the Vaccine Call Center's power tool that we tried out.

00:05:11.299 --> 00:05:15.380
And then something else happened, in that this website started to be passed around between

00:05:15.380 --> 00:05:16.420
people.

00:05:16.420 --> 00:05:17.420
And it's not a real website.

00:05:17.420 --> 00:05:18.420
It's not a real product.

00:05:18.420 --> 00:05:21.820
But over the course of a weekend, all of a sudden, there's hundreds of people using this

00:05:21.820 --> 00:05:24.380
website and signing up for appointments.

00:05:24.380 --> 00:05:26.619
And we're hearing back, and people are having a good experience.

00:05:26.619 --> 00:05:28.980
So we know that there's something there.

00:05:28.980 --> 00:05:31.700
But it turned into an unexpected launch.

00:05:31.700 --> 00:05:33.820
We've got this product, this prototype.

00:05:33.820 --> 00:05:34.820
But the state liked it.

00:05:34.820 --> 00:05:35.820
They wanted to use it.

00:05:35.820 --> 00:05:38.779
So we developed a really quick partnership with the state health departments, the Anchorage

00:05:38.779 --> 00:05:42.339
Health Department, and the Emergency Operations Center.

00:05:42.339 --> 00:05:46.540
And nobody from Alaska can do a presentation without a map of Alaska.

00:05:46.540 --> 00:05:49.420
But I just want to clarify, I work for the city of Anchorage.

00:05:49.420 --> 00:05:54.299
So we're the biggest city in Alaska, about 40% of the state's population.

00:05:54.299 --> 00:05:59.619
But what the state wants to do is to use this scraping-based vaccine finder for the entire

00:05:59.619 --> 00:06:00.619
state.

00:06:00.619 --> 00:06:04.220
So they want to use it in Fairbanks and Juneau and Ketchikan and Kodiak.

00:06:04.220 --> 00:06:06.500
And I'd say that's awesome, that's great.

00:06:06.500 --> 00:06:08.660
But we have to scramble here.

00:06:08.660 --> 00:06:11.700
And so over the course of the week, we cleaned up the scraper.

00:06:11.700 --> 00:06:14.339
We made it real by buying a domain.

00:06:14.339 --> 00:06:16.600
And about one week later, we launched.

00:06:16.600 --> 00:06:20.859
So we had an Alaska statewide vaccine finder tool.

00:06:20.859 --> 00:06:23.700
It's what I showed before, but basically cleaned up.

00:06:23.700 --> 00:06:28.619
It's appointments that you can find by location, address, vaccine type.

00:06:28.619 --> 00:06:32.339
It's text above, you know, on the phone that works well.

00:06:32.339 --> 00:06:33.339
And that's it.

00:06:33.459 --> 00:06:36.619
That's what we generated, and that's what we started using.

00:06:36.619 --> 00:06:41.019
And so over the course of January and February, we used this for things like signing up people

00:06:41.019 --> 00:06:44.899
for these big mass vaccination clinics at a basketball arena.

00:06:44.899 --> 00:06:51.059
Or when we launched drive-through clinics at hockey arenas, we signed people up through

00:06:51.059 --> 00:06:52.059
this website.

00:06:52.059 --> 00:06:53.459
So that's a lot of fun.

00:06:53.459 --> 00:06:54.700
And we got some good feedback.

00:06:54.700 --> 00:06:57.540
People were able to use this to connect to their appointments.

00:06:57.540 --> 00:07:02.859
And this tool was doing what we hoped it was doing.

00:07:03.380 --> 00:07:07.380
But it wasn't always straightforward, it wasn't always easy, and things definitely don't always

00:07:07.380 --> 00:07:09.140
go according to plan.

00:07:09.140 --> 00:07:14.739
So on March 9th, 2021, we got word that the governor was going to make a big announcement.

00:07:14.739 --> 00:07:18.700
Alaska was going to be the first state in the country to go fully open for everybody.

00:07:18.700 --> 00:07:23.299
Everybody age 16 and above would be able to get their vaccine appointments.

00:07:23.299 --> 00:07:28.380
So at 4.44 p.m., I had to send this message to my boss.

00:07:28.380 --> 00:07:32.299
The website was down, we had some weird data come across the scraper, and at the moment

00:07:32.299 --> 00:07:35.299
that we were expecting the biggest surge in traffic, maybe the highest amount of interest

00:07:35.299 --> 00:07:39.220
over the course of the entire rollout, I have to deal with this.

00:07:39.220 --> 00:07:43.459
But I was able to filter it out, keep it online, and I was really happy that we could put this

00:07:43.459 --> 00:07:47.459
banner up saying everybody age 16 and older can now get their vaccine in Alaska.

00:07:47.459 --> 00:07:52.459
So we stayed online throughout that pretty busy day.

00:07:52.459 --> 00:07:55.980
And over the course of this project, we didn't have the most stable website, we didn't have

00:07:55.980 --> 00:08:01.179
the fanciest website, we didn't have the fastest website, but our measure of success was how

00:08:01.179 --> 00:08:05.940
fast can we adapt to everything, adapt to new eligibility, adapt to new data, adapt

00:08:05.940 --> 00:08:13.660
to new pharmacies, adapt to new requirements, and that's exactly what we had to do.

00:08:13.660 --> 00:08:17.940
This vaccine rollout was one where Alaska was first, and we couldn't copy anybody else.

00:08:17.940 --> 00:08:21.940
We couldn't copy California or New York or Washington, but we kind of had to make it

00:08:21.940 --> 00:08:23.179
up as we go.

00:08:23.179 --> 00:08:27.040
If we could copy, we would, but we just couldn't.

00:08:27.040 --> 00:08:30.420
In some projects, the timelines aren't what you expect.

00:08:31.019 --> 00:08:35.640
In early January, we heard a really optimistic timeline that vaccines would be open by the

00:08:35.640 --> 00:08:36.640
summer solstice.

00:08:36.640 --> 00:08:42.159
So approximately a six-month rollout of those vaccines before they open up.

00:08:42.159 --> 00:08:47.679
But here it was March 9th, and it's the Iditarod Trail sled dog race, and we've got vaccines

00:08:47.679 --> 00:08:48.880
rolling out to everybody.

00:08:48.880 --> 00:08:54.359
So this whole project moved even faster than we ever really had expected.

00:08:54.359 --> 00:08:59.679
And we rode those waves throughout January and February as we opened up to younger people,

00:08:59.700 --> 00:09:01.380
as we opened up to new eligibility.

00:09:01.380 --> 00:09:03.700
And we got some, for Alaska, some major traffic.

00:09:03.700 --> 00:09:08.099
We'd see 20,000, 40,000 page views on a given day.

00:09:08.099 --> 00:09:14.659
And for this scraping-based website that has no backup and no team besides myself and my

00:09:14.659 --> 00:09:16.380
boss, we got a million page views.

00:09:16.380 --> 00:09:21.099
We connected the thousands of Alaskans to their appointments, and it served as the Alaska

00:09:21.099 --> 00:09:25.820
statewide vaccine finder tool for many months.

00:09:25.820 --> 00:09:30.820
And on a personal note, I got my very first piece of fan mail for an R project.

00:09:30.820 --> 00:09:35.640
And I definitely sent this to my boss as soon as I got that email.

00:09:35.640 --> 00:09:40.039
But as we moved out of those really crazy days of the early pandemic, we wanted to turn

00:09:40.039 --> 00:09:41.760
this into something more stable.

00:09:41.760 --> 00:09:48.020
I'd spent enough time trying to fix a scraper at 9 p.m. or 6 a.m., and one of the big changes

00:09:48.020 --> 00:09:53.820
was that we started with one major data source, and that's scraping this system called PrepMod.

00:09:53.820 --> 00:09:56.239
But all of a sudden, we were bringing in all sorts of other data.

00:09:56.239 --> 00:09:57.719
We've got pharmacy APIs.

00:09:57.719 --> 00:10:01.679
We've got some open-source project that brings in pharmacy chains.

00:10:01.679 --> 00:10:06.039
Vaccines.gov came on board, and we accessed some of that CDC data.

00:10:06.039 --> 00:10:10.580
And then all of a sudden, this simple project turns into kind of a complex project with

00:10:10.580 --> 00:10:13.640
six different opportunities for things to break.

00:10:13.640 --> 00:10:18.520
And what I was definitely overdue to do was to turn all these into modules so that when

00:10:18.520 --> 00:10:20.460
something breaks, you can turn it off.

00:10:20.460 --> 00:10:24.520
When something needs to be troubleshooted, you can target that in its own individual

00:10:24.520 --> 00:10:27.559
file and its own individual function.

00:10:27.559 --> 00:10:33.159
And it made it from a brittle website into a less brittle website.

00:10:33.159 --> 00:10:37.080
I also tried to bring in more error handling.

00:10:37.080 --> 00:10:39.719
Errors would break the website in the early days for sure.

00:10:39.719 --> 00:10:44.000
So I brought in a bunch more try-catch statements so that you can run a statement, and if it

00:10:44.000 --> 00:10:46.700
successfully executes, you get your data back.

00:10:46.880 --> 00:10:50.479
But if and when that error comes, we can still return some valid data.

00:10:50.479 --> 00:10:54.200
We can still keep the rest of the sources online, and we don't break the system just

00:10:54.200 --> 00:10:57.960
because those errors did come.

00:10:57.960 --> 00:11:02.619
For automation, we really wanted to track appointments 24-7, because they were really

00:11:02.619 --> 00:11:06.039
going fast in those early days, and so we wanted to scrape every single minute to see

00:11:06.039 --> 00:11:09.679
how close we could keep up with vaccine appointments.

00:11:09.679 --> 00:11:16.239
And the way I did this was with a Heroku R buildpack and a Heroku cron job, where I basically

00:11:16.239 --> 00:11:21.179
ran one script every 10 minutes, and then in those 10 minutes, I scraped several times.

00:11:21.179 --> 00:11:24.059
So seven or 10 times every 10 minutes.

00:11:24.059 --> 00:11:28.219
We scraped and we scraped and we scraped and we scraped, and about 5 million HTML pages

00:11:28.219 --> 00:11:31.659
I think we scraped before we finally moved off of that scraper.

00:11:31.659 --> 00:11:36.500
So that prototype turned into something that got used quite a bit.

00:11:36.500 --> 00:11:40.859
We also had to adapt to the complexity that came up throughout the process of this.

00:11:40.880 --> 00:11:42.880
If you may remember, there's a lot of phases.

00:11:42.880 --> 00:11:48.799
There's phase 1b, tier 1, phase 1a, tier 3, and we got a lot of requests to have information

00:11:48.799 --> 00:11:53.559
like this on the website, and we don't like too much complexity, and we're pretty militant

00:11:53.559 --> 00:11:56.960
about having simple information as much as possible.

00:11:56.960 --> 00:12:01.679
So the way that we did this on the front end was we kept the appointments above the fold,

00:12:01.679 --> 00:12:07.159
as they say, so appointments up high, but we radically simplified the eligibility information

00:12:07.159 --> 00:12:09.679
and kind of had it slightly hidden.

00:12:09.700 --> 00:12:14.859
But we kept the scope of this as narrow as we can to here's where you find your appointments.

00:12:14.859 --> 00:12:18.580
And then more complexity came in in that all of a sudden we've got a lot of vaccine appointments

00:12:18.580 --> 00:12:24.820
and supplies at a certain point, and it's turning into a big list that needs some management.

00:12:24.820 --> 00:12:28.299
And because we didn't want to add complicated menus and we wanted this to work really well

00:12:28.299 --> 00:12:34.780
on phones, what we did was just little HTML buttons that allows you to search this table

00:12:34.780 --> 00:12:39.340
for the city or region, and there's a lot of string searching going on in this.

00:12:39.340 --> 00:12:43.619
So that was our strategy for dealing with that complexity.

00:12:43.619 --> 00:12:46.159
So what have I learned throughout this experience?

00:12:46.159 --> 00:12:51.679
One is that there's a really subtle power to creating an MVP, to creating a demo.

00:12:51.679 --> 00:12:57.520
So if we had asked in advance permission to do this website, we would have encountered

00:12:57.520 --> 00:12:58.880
a lot of reasons to say no.

00:12:58.880 --> 00:13:04.080
It's like what's your budget, what's the plan, what's your backup plan, who's the staff in

00:13:04.080 --> 00:13:05.340
charge of this?

00:13:05.340 --> 00:13:10.340
But when you put something in the hands of people where they can interact with it and

00:13:10.340 --> 00:13:14.140
break through all those barriers, there's really a lot of magic to it.

00:13:14.140 --> 00:13:16.979
And these prototypes, in our case, they're not pretty.

00:13:16.979 --> 00:13:23.539
They're text on a phone, but sometimes a prototype, just a proof of concept, can sometimes blow

00:13:23.539 --> 00:13:28.479
people's minds just enough to break through and make progress on projects.

00:13:28.479 --> 00:13:33.340
There's also some secret value in building your own dataset.

00:13:33.599 --> 00:13:38.479
And in this case, we were kind of the only people scraping and aggregating appointments

00:13:38.479 --> 00:13:40.440
across the state of Alaska.

00:13:40.440 --> 00:13:46.080
And because we wanted to track how many appointments there were, we had the tools to do that, and

00:13:46.080 --> 00:13:50.880
I displayed how many appointments were available at any given moment throughout the day.

00:13:50.880 --> 00:13:54.440
And this was basically out of curiosity because we wanted to see how fast things were going.

00:13:54.440 --> 00:13:57.219
But at some point, we learned that the state health department was actually watching this

00:13:57.219 --> 00:14:02.340
number and actually using that number to make decisions on when it's time to open up eligibility

00:14:02.340 --> 00:14:05.000
or when it's time to make some changes.

00:14:05.000 --> 00:14:10.080
So when you build that dataset, sometimes you have the ability to find value and find

00:14:10.080 --> 00:14:15.559
unexpected value in places that you didn't intend.

00:14:15.559 --> 00:14:23.760
So R is a great prototyping tool, especially with all of you who love R and have spent

00:14:23.760 --> 00:14:25.219
some time with it.

00:14:25.219 --> 00:14:31.719
This project was a series of data frames that basically would be created, updated, modified,

00:14:31.739 --> 00:14:35.020
and then destroyed every single minute is what we would do.

00:14:35.020 --> 00:14:39.500
And because I'm comfortable manipulating data frames, that's what I did.

00:14:39.500 --> 00:14:45.219
And it's ultimately this data frame that took a lot of work, but that data frame turns into

00:14:45.219 --> 00:14:46.219
the product.

00:14:46.219 --> 00:14:51.659
It's the world's simplest database that is JSON or CSV, but that turns into the actual

00:14:51.659 --> 00:14:52.659
product.

00:14:52.659 --> 00:15:00.979
So if you have that ability to work fast in R, you're really set up well to create prototypes.

00:15:00.979 --> 00:15:07.219
And in some projects, if this project had a different timeline, and we knew we had months

00:15:07.219 --> 00:15:12.340
to work on this, I may have used something more traditional like Node.js or Python or

00:15:12.340 --> 00:15:16.340
something more standard to build out a web service and a website and maybe use some React

00:15:16.340 --> 00:15:20.900
